<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Trail Ridge Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Trail Ridge Road</h2><p><i>Colorado, USA · US-34 across Rocky Mountain NP, Estes Park to Grand Lake</i></p><p><b>Highest continuously paved road in North America (3,713 m); 18 km above tree line.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>50 km (31 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2 hrs no stops; half day with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Memorial Day–mid October (closes with first heavy snow)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Altitude (over 3,600 m on tundra); afternoon thunderstorms; no guardrails on tundra; sudden temperature drops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>108</td></tr></table><hr><p>Opened 1932, this road gives lower-48 motorists their best taste of the Arctic. The 18 km above tree line are an alpine tundra ecosystem identical in plant species to northern Alaska. Plants grow no taller than your ankle — those tiny cushions of moss campion may be 200 years old. Step off the trail and you may kill decades of growth. Storms build by early afternoon; cross the high section in the morning. Elk are everywhere.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Many Parks Curve</b> — Boardwalk overlook of the Estes Park glacial bowl with the Mummy Range behind. Often elk in fall meadows below.</li><li><b>Forest Canyon overlook</b> — 3,572 m. You're looking 700 m straight down into a textbook glacial U-valley with the Never Summer range opposite.</li><li><b>Gore Range overlook</b> — Highest paved point in the contiguous USA at 3,719 m. Eighteen named mountain ranges visible on a clear day.</li><li><b>Alpine Visitor Center</b> — 3,595 m — the highest visitor center in the National Park Service. Tundra-life interpretive trail; oxygen feels noticeably thin.</li><li><b>Milner Pass</b> — Crosses the Continental Divide at 3,279 m. The lake here drains both to the Pacific and the Atlantic depending on which side of the road snowmelt lands.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
